definitions: blessed with good luck or favorable circumstances in life
resulting in something good or favorable happening by chance
examples: She was fortunate to find her lost wallet
The fortunate students received full scholarships
It was fortunate timing that the rain stopped
Their fortunate meeting led to a successful partnership

definitions: being four times ten in number or amount
examples: She celebrated her forty years of service
The temperature reached forty degrees Celsius yesterday

definitions: preserved as a fossil through natural processes over geological time
examples: Scientists discovered fossilised dinosaur bones in the desert
The fossilised leaves showed incredible detail

definitions: preserved as a fossil through natural processes over geological time
remaining unchanged for so long as to seem antiquated or rigid
examples: The museum displayed fossilized shells from ancient seas
Archaeologists found fossilized footprints in the rock
His fossilized teaching methods failed to engage modern students
The company's fossilized policies needed urgent updating

definitions: having an offensive smell, taste, or appearance that causes disgust
breaking the rules of a game or sport unfairly
morally offensive, wicked, or disgraceful in nature
examples: The foul odor from the garbage made everyone leave
We couldn't drink the foul-tasting water
The referee called a foul play during the match
His foul tackle injured the opposing player
She used foul language that shocked her parents
The criminal's foul deeds horrified the community

definitions: made dirty, polluted, or contaminated with unwanted substances
tangled, clogged, or blocked preventing normal operation
examples: The oil spill fouled the pristine beach waters
Industrial waste fouled the river for miles downstream
The fishing net became fouled in the propeller
Seaweed fouled the boat's anchor chain

definitions: being one more than three in number
examples: The table has four sturdy wooden legs
She bought four tickets for tonight's concert

definitions: being four times as great or as many in amount
examples: Company profits increased fourfold in just two years
The population experienced a fourfold growth since 1950

definitions: marked by firm, unwavering conviction or expression that is direct
having four equal sides forming a square shape
examples: He stood foursquare behind his controversial decision
The senator remained foursquare in her principles
The foursquare building dominated the town center
They built a foursquare tower on the hilltop

definitions: being four more than ten in number
examples: The recipe requires fourteen different spices
She will turn fourteen on her next birthday

definitions: coming after thirteen others in a series or sequence
examples: The fourteenth amendment guarantees equal protection under law
He finished fourteenth in the marathon race

definitions: coming after three others in a series or sequence
being one of four equal parts of something
examples: She came fourth in the swimming competition
The fourth chapter explains the main theory
He ate a fourth of the pizza himself
The fourth quarter showed improved sales figures

definitions: showing cleverness or cunning typical of a fox
sexually attractive in a bold or flirtatious way
examples: His foxy business tactics outsmarted the competition
She gave a foxy smile before revealing her plan
She looked foxy in her red evening dress
The foxy actress captivated audiences with her charm

definitions: constituting a very small part or amount of something
relating to or expressed as a mathematical fraction
examples: The medicine showed only fractional improvement in symptoms
There was fractional movement in the stock price
Students learned fractional arithmetic in math class
The fractional values needed careful calculation

definitions: easily irritated, bad-tempered, and likely to cause trouble or arguments
examples: The fractious toddler refused to take a nap
Managing the fractious committee required great patience

definitions: easily broken, shattered, or damaged requiring careful handling
lacking in strength, force, or effectiveness making it vulnerable
examples: Handle the fragile glassware with extreme care
The antique vase was too fragile to transport
Their fragile peace agreement could collapse at any moment
His fragile health required constant medical attention

definitions: consisting of small disconnected parts rather than a complete whole
examples: The archaeologists found only fragmentary evidence of the civilization
Her fragmentary memories made testimony difficult

definitions: broken into pieces or parts that are disconnected or incomplete
examples: The fragmented mirror reflected distorted images
Society became increasingly fragmented along political lines

definitions: having a pleasant, sweet smell that is enjoyable to experience
examples: The fragrant roses filled the garden with perfume
She added fragrant herbs to the cooking pot

definitions: physically weak and delicate, especially from age or illness
easily broken or destroyed due to lack of strength
examples: The frail elderly woman needed help walking
His frail body couldn't withstand the harsh treatment
The frail wooden bridge swayed dangerously in wind
Their frail alliance broke under the first pressure

definitions: enclosed in a border or supporting structure for display
falsely made to appear guilty of a crime
examples: The framed photograph hung prominently on the wall
She kept framed certificates in her office
The innocent man was framed for the robbery
Evidence suggested the suspect had been framed

definitions: open, honest, and direct in speech or writing without deception
examples: She appreciated his frank assessment of her performance
Let me be frank about the company's problems

definitions: wild or distraught with fear, anxiety, or other emotion
done quickly and with little organization due to urgency
examples: The frantic mother searched everywhere for her child
His frantic screams alerted the neighbors
They made frantic preparations before the storm arrived
The frantic pace of work left everyone exhausted

definitions: relating to or typical of brothers or a brotherly relationship
examples: The fraternal bond between the soldiers was unbreakable
He joined a fraternal organization for mutual support

definitions: obtained, done by, or involving deception especially criminal deception for gain
examples: The company faced charges for fraudulent accounting practices
Police investigated the fraudulent insurance claims

definitions: causing or affected by great anxiety or stress
filled with or likely to result in something undesirable
examples: The fraught negotiations lasted through the night
She felt fraught with worry about the results
The journey was fraught with unexpected dangers
Their relationship was fraught with misunderstandings

definitions: worn out with threads coming apart at the edges
showing signs of strain, tension, or deterioration
examples: His frayed collar showed years of wear
The rope became frayed from constant use
Tempers were frayed after the long debate
Their frayed relationship finally ended in divorce

definitions: very strange, unusual, or unexpected in a disturbing way
examples: The freaky weather patterns concerned climate scientists
She had a freaky dream about flying elephants

definitions: born as a free person, not as a slave or serf
examples: Freeborn citizens had more rights than former slaves
The freeborn child inherited his father's status

definitions: drawn or done by hand without mechanical aids or instruments
examples: The architect sketched a freehand drawing of the building
Her freehand calligraphy impressed everyone at the exhibition

definitions: working for different companies at different times rather than permanently employed
examples: The freelance writer worked from her home office
He chose freelance consulting over corporate employment

definitions: standing alone or independently without being attached to anything else
examples: They installed a freestanding bathtub in the bathroom
The freestanding sculpture dominated the gallery space

definitions: not bound by formal rules or conventions, acting freely and spontaneously
examples: His freewheeling lifestyle worried his conservative parents
The freewheeling discussion produced many creative ideas

definitions: fast and energetic in a wild and uncontrolled way
examples: The frenetic pace of city life exhausted him
Shoppers moved at a frenetic speed during sales

definitions: wildly excited or uncontrolled due to intense emotion or activity
examples: The frenzied crowd pushed toward the stage
She worked at a frenzied pace to meet deadlines

definitions: decorated with repeated ornamental patterns of interlaced lines
constantly worried or anxious about something
examples: The fretted ceiling showed intricate geometric designs
He played the fretted instrument with great skill
She fretted about her children's safety constantly
The manager fretted over declining sales figures

definitions: denoting a type of consonant made by forcing air through narrow channel
examples: The fricative sounds in English include f and v
Students practiced pronouncing fricative consonants correctly

definitions: relating to or caused by friction between two surfaces in contact
examples: Frictional forces slowed the sliding box considerably
The engineer calculated frictional losses in the system

definitions: cooked by immersing in hot fat or oil
mentally or physically exhausted from overwork or stress
examples: She ordered fried chicken with mashed potatoes
The fried eggs sizzled in the pan
After the long shift, he felt completely fried
My brain is fried from studying all night

definitions: having no friends, lacking companionship or social connections
examples: The friendless boy ate lunch alone every day
Moving abroad left her feeling friendless and isolated

definitions: afraid or anxious due to perceived danger or threat
examples: The frightened child hid behind her mother
Frightened investors sold their stocks during the crash

definitions: making someone afraid or anxious by presenting danger or threat
examples: The frightening movie gave children nightmares
Climate change presents frightening challenges for humanity

definitions: very bad, unpleasant, or shocking in nature or appearance
causing fear or terror through being horrifying
examples: The storm caused frightful damage to coastal towns
She had a frightful headache all morning
The frightful screams echoed through the haunted house
He told frightful stories around the campfire

definitions: very cold in temperature, especially uncomfortably so
lacking emotional warmth, friendliness, or enthusiasm
examples: The frigid Arctic winds froze everything instantly
They endured frigid temperatures during the expedition
Her frigid response discouraged further conversation
The frigid atmosphere made the meeting uncomfortable

definitions: having a decorative border of hanging threads or strips
examples: She wore a fringed leather jacket to the concert
The fringed lampshade added vintage charm to the room

definitions: playful and full of energy in a lively, spirited way
examples: The frisky puppy jumped around the yard excitedly
She felt frisky after her morning coffee

definitions: not having any serious purpose or value, concerned with trivial matters
examples: The court dismissed his frivolous lawsuit immediately
She spent money on frivolous purchases she didn't need

definitions: relating to the front part of something
direct and straightforward in approach, often confrontational
examples: The frontal lobe controls important cognitive functions
The car sustained frontal damage in the collision
They launched a frontal assault on the fortress
Her frontal criticism surprised everyone at the meeting

definitions: covered with frost or a frost-like substance
having a translucent, textured surface that obscures clear vision
examples: The frosted windows sparkled in the morning sun
Frosted branches created a winter wonderland scene
She chose frosted glass for bathroom privacy
The baker decorated cakes with frosted icing

definitions: very cold with frost forming or likely to form
cold and unfriendly in manner showing disapproval or dislike
examples: The frosty morning air made their breath visible
Farmers worried about frosty nights damaging crops
She gave him a frosty reception at the party
Their frosty relationship never improved after the argument
